They are described as non-essential staffs who have been working to end the Ebola outbreak. A WHO spokesperson said more than 70 colleagues would remain there. On Monday, two people were killed in clashes with police after protesters set fire to the mayor of Beni's office and several UN buildings. The violence was an angry response to an escalation of attacks by armed groups in the region. People are demanding better protection from the Congolese army and UN peacekeepers. --BBC--